<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="77" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="12" pageNumber="77">Distribution and ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="12" pageNumber="77">Europe (Estonia, Finland, Germany, Norway, Russia - up to Ural Mts.), North America, on medium-decayed wood of angiosperms.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="77" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="12" pageNumber="77">Remarks</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="12" pageNumber="77">
. The type specimen of 
<taxonomicName class="Agaricomycetes" family="Schizoporaceae" genus="Hyphodontia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Hyphodontia nikolajevae" order="Hymenochaetales" pageId="12" pageNumber="77" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="nikolajevae">Hyphodontia nikolajevae</taxonomicName>
Parmasto reveals no essential differences from the type and other collections of 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. pruinosus" pageId="12" pageNumber="77" rank="species" species="pruinosus">X. pruinosus</taxonomicName>
studied by us. On average, 
<taxonomicName class="Agaricomycetes" family="Schizoporaceae" genus="Xylodon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Xylodon pruinosus" order="Hymenochaetales" pageId="12" pageNumber="77" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="pruinosus">Xylodon pruinosus</taxonomicName>
has wider basidiospores than 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. detriticus" pageId="12" pageNumber="77" rank="species" species="detriticus">X. detriticus</taxonomicName>
(Table 2).
</paragraph>
